        output='Based on the provided text, the timeline for the **"second half of 2026"** is associated with two major, interdependent milestones: the commencement of Starship\'s orbital payload delivery and the deployment of next-generation V3 Starlink satellites. \n\nHere is the exact language and the qualifying/conditional language surrounding these timelines:\n\n### 1. Starship Payload Delivery to Orbit\n**Exact Language:**\n* *"We expect Starship to commence payload delivery to orbit in the second half of 2026."*\n* *"We expect Starship to commence payload delivery to orbit in the second half of 2026 following additional flight tests."*\n\n**Qualifying & Conditional Language:**\n* **Forward-Looking Qualifier:** The use of **"We expect"** frames the timeline as an anticipation rather than a guaranteed date.\n* **Operational Prerequisite:** The timeline is explicitly conditioned on the completion of **"following additional flight tests."** \n* **Explicit Risk/Delay Conditions:** The text immediately follows the timeline with a cross-reference to developmental risks that could alter the schedule: *"For additional information about this risk, please refer to \'Risk Factors —Risks Related to Our Business—**Any failure or delay in the development of Starship at scale or in achieving the required launch cadence, reusability and capabilities thereafter would delay or limit our ability to execute our growth strategy...\'"***\n\n### 2. Deployment of Next-Generation V3 Satellites\n**Exact Language:**\n* *"We expect to commence deploying our next-generation V3 satellites, designed to offer one Tbps of downlink capacity per satellite, using Starship in the second half of 2026..."*\n* *"...and in the second half of 2026, we expect to begin deployment of our next-generation V3 satellites, each of which is designed to offer one Tbps of downlink capacity per satellite."*\n\n**Qualifying & Conditional Language:**\n* **Forward-Looking Qualifiers:** Phrases like **"We expect to commence deploying"** and **"we expect to begin"** indicate that this is a targeted goal subject to change.\n* **Technological Dependency:** The deployment is strictly conditioned on the successful operationalization of the new rocket, noted by the phrase **"using Starship."** Therefore, the V3 deployment timeline is entirely dependent on Starship achieving its own "second half of 2026" payload delivery milestone.\n* **Performance Expectations:** The text attaches further forward-looking conditions to the *results* of these deployments: *"...and **expect that** a single Starship launch **will be capable of** deploying up to 60 V3 satellites to LEO, representing a potential twenty-fold increase in Starlink downlink capacity deployed relative to a Falcon 9 launch."*\n\n### Summary of Conditions\nThe "second half of 2026" timeline is heavily caveated. It is not a fixed date but a **forward-looking expectation ("we expect")** that is strictly **conditional upon the successful execution of prerequisite "additional flight tests."** Furthermore, the company explicitly warns that any "failure or delay" in achieving Starship\'s reusability, scale, or launch cadence will directly delay this timeline and the subsequent deployment of the V3 satellite constellation.',
